First, mentorship must become intentional. Experienced scientists should reach out to women early in their careers, offering guidance on navigating grant applications and building collaborations. Second, hiring committees need structured rubrics that focus on skill sets rather than gut impressions. Third, funding agencies can set aside dedicated calls for underrepresented groups, ensuring diverse teams have the resources they need. Finally, visibility matters: celebrating women’s achievements publicly normalizes their presence in STEM.

